<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFAFAB0FFF2D8D70FE22FA7B" pageId="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFAFAB0FFF2D8D70FE22FA7B" blockId="13.[173,660,1283,1729]" pageId="13">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFF2D8D70FEDCFA8E" bold="true" box="[197,301,1363,1384]" pageId="13">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFED38D71FDEDFA81" box="[315,540,1362,1383]" italics="true" pageId="13">
<taxonomicName id="4C719CFCFFAFAB0FFED38D71FDF5FA81" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2014" box="[315,516,1362,1383]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hermani">Pujoliclerus hermani</taxonomicName>
is
</emphasis>
distinguishable from other members of the genus by the pale yellow coloration of the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFAFAB0FFF2D8D80FBECFEBA" pageId="13" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFAFAB0FFF2D8D80FBEBFEC1" blockId="13.[173,660,1283,1729]" lastBlockId="13.[707,1193,194,587]" pageId="13">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFF2D8D80FE8AFA5E" bold="true" box="[197,379,1443,1464]" pageId="13">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 6.0 mm; width 12.0 mm. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFEF38D9EFEA5FA34" bold="true" box="[283,340,1469,1490]" pageId="13">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFAFAB0FFE448D9EFDF7FA34" box="[428,518,1469,1490]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="22.[175,215,1444,1463]" captionTargetBox="[167,1157,203,1421]" captionTargetId="figure-120@22.[167,1157,192,1421]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figs. 98–103. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 98) P. ovatus; 99) P. wappesi; 100) P. amplus; 101) P. flavoapicalus;" pageId="13">Fig. 103</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFDFD8D9EFD7DFA34" bold="true" box="[533,652,1469,1490]" pageId="13">Integument</emphasis>
: Head mostly yellow, with rectangular black marking on vertex; antenna mostly black, scape mostly yellow, last antennomere yellow; pronotal disc broadly black, sides broadly yellow; elytra light yellow; legs mostly yellow, tibiae infuscated; pterothorax and abdomen brown. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFDE98E7EFDC9F994" bold="true" box="[513,568,1629,1650]" pageId="13">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes as wide as frons (14:14); funicular antennomeres slightly expanded (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFAFAB0FFE998EB1FE4CF941" box="[369,445,1682,1703]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="13">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFE3B8EB1FDD0F941" bold="true" box="[467,545,1682,1703]" pageId="13">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum slightly transverse (40:38), lateral tubercle very prominent (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFAFAB0FFCD588E1FC7FFF31" box="[829,910,194,215]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="18.[175,215,1395,1414]" captionTargetBox="[151,1155,183,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-114@18.[151,1172,183,1383]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs. 48–61. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 48) P. helvinus; 49) P. maracayensis; 50) P. modestus; 51) P. bilineatus; 52) P. calceatus; 53) P. corumba; 54) P. flavolimbatus; 55) P. ovatus; 56) P. wappesi; 57) P. amplus; 58) P. flavoapicalus; 59) P. gilvus; 60) P. hermani; 61) P. orellana." pageId="13">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold gradually diminishings to elytral apex; asetiferous punctures prominent to elytral apex. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFC3C88D4FBCDFEEA" bold="true" box="[980,1084,247,268]" pageId="13">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tegminal lobes and phallic apex as in 
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFAFAB0FFC388931FBE7FEC1" box="[976,1046,274,295]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="20.[175,215,1170,1189]" captionTargetBox="[164,629,189,1147]" captionTargetId="figure-461@20.[151,638,183,1159]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs. 76–91. Pujoliclerus species, aedeagi. 76) P. helvinus; 77) P. bilineatus; 78) P. calceatus; 79) P. corumba; 80) P. flavolimbatus; 81) P. ovatus (tegmen only); 82) P. wappesi; 83) P. gilvus; 84) P. hermani; 85) P. casselorum; 86) P. catarina (phallus only); 87) P. argus; 88) P. aspigalbus; 89) P. flora; 90) P. posticalis; 91) P. pallidus." pageId="13">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFAFAB0FFD33890FFBECFEBA" blockId="13.[707,1193,194,587]" pageId="13">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFD33890FFC78FEA7" bold="true" box="[731,905,300,321]" pageId="13">Natural History.</emphasis>
T h e t y p e w a s c o l l e c t e d during April, from streamside litter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFAFAB0FFD338941FBFFFE77" pageId="13" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFAFAB0FFD338941FBFFFE77" blockId="13.[707,1193,194,587]" pageId="13">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFD338941FCACFE91" bold="true" box="[731,861,354,375]" pageId="13">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54CA59DDFFAFAB0FFB928941FB58FE91" box="[1146,1193,354,375]" pageId="13">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry id="F366A7EFFFAFAB0FFCDC895FFC66FE77" box="[820,919,380,401]" name="Venezuela" pageId="13">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFAFAB0FFC41895FFBF2FE77" box="[937,1027,380,401]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="27.[197,228,861,880]" captionTargetBox="[174,1193,183,838]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Fig. 124. Geographic distribution of seven Pujoliclerus species." pageId="13">Fig. 124</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFAFAB0FFD3389B4FBDFFDAD" pageId="13" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFAFAB0FFD3389B4FBDFFDAD" blockId="13.[707,1193,194,587]" pageId="13">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFAFAB0FFD3389B4FCBCFE4A" bold="true" box="[731,845,407,428]" pageId="13">Etymology.</emphasis>
I dedicate this species to Lee Herman for his unfailing companionship during several expeditions to Latin America (with one exception, he nearly let me drown in a downpour on Cerro Campana, 
<collectingCountry id="F366A7EFFFAFAB0FFC7C8A22FC13FDF0" box="[916,994,513,534]" name="Panama" pageId="13">Panama</collectingCountry>
, while he frolicked around in our fancy rental vehicle, searching for those insignificant litter beetles).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
